This directory contains an EventSerializer of the Broker Binary V1 format, but
without using the broker::data model.


The any Decoding Misery
=======================

When sending events that contain either ``any`` parameters, or any nested record
fields or tables that have ``any`` keys or values, it cannot be fully decoded to
the expected type, because the expected type is ``any``.

Previously, this was "solved" by parsing everything into the basic broker::data model
which boils down to vector, table or sets of atomic types, or an atomic broker::data
type directly, then wrapping this into the Broker::Data type.

We can continue to do this, but instead of parsing into broker::data, we parse
into vector of any, table[any] of any or set[any] if there's not enough type
information available. It's not clear this needs an extra Broker::Data like wrap,
but casting should still function.

So, e.g.

type R: record {
  a: count;
  b: string;
}

local rv: vector of any;
rv += 42;
rv += "forty-two";

# Can we do this? Take a vector of any and make it a record?
 if ( rv ?as R )
   local r = rv as R;

# Neither of these work, which I think is good. But that also means
# we cannot expose them.
table[any] of any?
set[any]

# So if there is a set or table in the message, what are the options?
#
# Decode as a vector of pairs?
# That's anyhow how it's encoded.
# If there's nested tables, that's pretty crappy, but should work
# recursively still.
#
# The nice part is we don't have to construct the table during parsing,
# something that the broker implementation did.
Cluster::Table
  entries: vector of any = [[key, value], [key, value], ...]

Cluster::Set
  entries: vector of any = [key, key, ...]
